# Build environment (Rust / Cargo)

Agent and terminal shells may not have `PATH` set like a normal user login. To avoid "cargo: command not found" and linker flakiness:

## NVIDIA CUDA / `nvcc` (Windows)

- **Install location (this workspace):** `C:\Program Files\NVIDIA GPU Computing Toolkit\CUDA\v13.1\bin\nvcc.exe`.
- **Persistent user `PATH`:** Ensure **User** environment variable `Path` includes:
  - `C:\Program Files\NVIDIA GPU Computing Toolkit\CUDA\v13.1\bin`
  - (optional) `...\v13.1\bin\x64`
- **Cursor / VS Code integrated terminals:** Repo **`.vscode/settings.json`** sets `terminal.integrated.env.windows` so **`CUDA_PATH`** and **`PATH`** prepend the CUDA 13.1 `bin` dirs before `${env:PATH}` (helps when the agent shell is minimal). Reload the window or open a **new** terminal after pull.
- **Agent tool calls (no inherited PATH):** invoke NVCC by full path when probes fail:
  - `& "C:\Program Files\NVIDIA GPU Computing Toolkit\CUDA\v13.1\bin\nvcc.exe" --version`
- **`vox ci build-timings` / `cuda-features`:** These spawn `nvcc` on `PATH`. If a job still skips CUDA, set in that shell:  
  `$env:PATH = "C:\Program Files\NVIDIA GPU Computing Toolkit\CUDA\v13.1\bin;C:\Program Files\NVIDIA GPU Computing Toolkit\CUDA\v13.1\bin\x64;" + $env:PATH`  
  and `$env:CUDA_PATH = "C:\Program Files\NVIDIA GPU Computing Toolkit\CUDA\v13.1"`.
- **User PATH repair (all apps, new processes):** `vox doctor --fix-cuda-path` (idempotent; sets **User** `Path` + `CUDA_PATH`). The legacy `scripts/windows/ensure_cuda_path.ps1` was removed ŌĆö use the CLI primitive. Other agent hosts that do not read `.vscode/settings.json` still see `nvcc` after a new shell.

## Running Cargo

- **Windows (PowerShell)**: Use the full path to Cargo so the command runs without relying on `PATH`:
  - `& "$env:USERPROFILE\.cargo\bin\cargo.exe" <args>`
- **Working directory**: Always run Cargo from the workspace root. Set `working_directory` to the repo root (e.g. `c:\Users\Owner\vox`) when invoking terminal commands.
- Prefer `cargo check --workspace` when only checking for compile errors (faster, less I/O than full `cargo build`). Use `cargo build --workspace` when artifacts are needed.
- **Populi Candle QLoRA + NVIDIA CUDA**: use **`cargo vox-cuda-release`** from the repo root (alias in `.cargo/config.toml` ŌåÆ `gpu,populi-candle-cuda`). On Windows, run from **Visual Studio x64 Native Tools** / `vcvars64.bat` so `nvcc` finds `cl.exe`. A plain `cargo build -p vox-cli --release` does **not** enable CUDA kernels; rebuild with the alias after `cargo clean` or when QLoRA falls back to CPU.
- If you see "file lock" or "user-mapped section" errors on Windows, another Cargo process may be holding the lock; retry once or use `cargo check` to avoid writing binaries.
- **`CARGO_TARGET_DIR` in your shell:** If you (or a script) set this to a side folder (e.g. `target-ci-check`), every `cargo build` / `cargo run` uses that directory instead of the repoŌĆÖs default `target` from `.cargo/config.toml`. That is fine for isolation, but remember to **clear it** when you want the normal layout again ŌĆö PowerShell: `$env:CARGO_TARGET_DIR = $null` in the **current** terminal (environment variables do not ŌĆ£stickŌĆØ in Git; only your session/user env might).
- **Turso / `aegis` on Windows (MSVC)**: The workspace `[patch.crates-io]` in the root `Cargo.toml` points `aegis` at `patches/aegis-0.9.8` with **`pure-rust`** in default features so the native C build is skipped. If you disable that patch or hit a `cc-rs` / `clang-cl.exe` error when building deps, install [LLVM for Windows](https://releases.llvm.org/) and prepend **`C:\Program Files\LLVM\bin`** to `PATH` (or set `CC` / `CXX` appropriately) so `clang-cl.exe` is found.

## Dev launcher (when `vox` is not on PATH)

- If `vox` is not globally installed, forward commands via local bootstrap shell scripts:
  - Windows: `pwsh -File scripts/windows/vox-dev.ps1 <command>`
  - Bash: `./scripts/vox-dev.sh <command>`

## Running tests

- Use `cargo test --workspace` for full test runs. For quick iteration, run tests per crate, e.g. `cargo test -p vox-cli` or a specific test name.
- On Windows, linking test binaries can occasionally fail with LNK1104; retrying the test run or running a subset of tests often succeeds.

## Reproducibility

- CI (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`) installs the stable Rust toolchain with `dtolnay/rust-toolchain@stable` and components `rustfmt`, `clippy`. Local agent runs should use the same toolchain (stable) when possible.
- For a reproducible sandbox, use the same Rust version as CI (see `rust-version` in root `Cargo.toml`).
